Duel to the last blood: MP3 players against cell phones
We'll advise you how to choose
While almost every cell phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
This makes it clear that it is best to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons to get a self-reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
You might not be able to buy an expensive high-quality recording to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, these music products do not come out as LP's and there is no objective reason for this from a qualitative point of view.
But if you have hard rock, jazz, or blues vinyl on your shelves, you're probably dreaming of a recording like that.
It also works with portable music, i.e. music compressed or simply in MP3 format.
Here too, there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan may hardly digest the 20-crown marketplace.
Two extremes between which there's enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It's the battery life that matters.
Some high-quality music players are able to do much more than just read music, which mobile phones do not by mistake.
There is no other device as universal today as the mobile phone.
Besides the primary functions, phone calls and texting, it can read music and videos, record both and it has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse, and maybe even navigate.
And if we consider smartphones and palm trees, you'll also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It's a little miracle, because no refrigerator can do the grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your cell phone, the sooner the indicator on the screen will require the battery.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than 12 hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simpler ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap phones, don't count them as lasting more than a few hours.
If you add in, from time to time, a few calls, get yourself another battery charger at work for safety, that goes for the most expensive appliances.
But you won't have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least nine hours on continuous function with a charge.
Another problem exists when you download music to your cell phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port and not all can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory players can do it without an adapter for minicards that are not used on mobile phones.
Readers, with a few exceptions (iPods) do not need any special software.
Just fill the machine with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and readers create a multimedia library by themselves, sorted by the performers' names, album name, genre or user classification.
Some devices only reproduce the tree structure of folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, cell phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, you should be particularly concerned with the battery's strength, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, clearly, ease of use.
If you need music primarily in the background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram, you'll need just any cell phone that reads MP3.
This is now possible, clearly, on any cell phone.
You don't have to worry too much about what formats your cell phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support all of them, and the majority of the music that gets to you will be in this format.
In addition to this format, which is among the most widely used, the majority of devices support music in WMA format.
Less is found in the AAC (formatting used by Apple and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
You just have to visit the corresponding pages of the operator (or another supplier) via the mobile internet and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a cell phone reader.
Unfortunately, the operators' offer is poor and is usually limited to the radio moment.
The prices aren't very low.
But it is generally assumed that this very way of selling music (either via GSM, the internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phones with them.
Anyone who wants to hear something is stuck in their pocket while the MP3 player is left behind at home.
But it also depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least the wireless earpiece.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small portion of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-reader devices is, for many, the price.
The cheaper ones usually cost less than 3,000 crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an entrance for the common headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones, and even the 3.5 mm headphone jack, cost up to 15 thousand crowns.
The advantage of readers is, among other things, easy handling.
The simplest ones, not necessarily the cheapest (see our choice), are really something anyone can handle.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling at one time to the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally stalling the launch of the mobile internet and consequently a giant data bill.
Which device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD, etc.).
Also for the purchase of the respective card, you are in the 2 000 krone.
But be careful.
The basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the more expensive ones can do it with 8GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and you want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) you must not spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, you prefer to use specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual MP3 keys and the convenience of service so you get closer to the same MP3 player.
In this area Sony Ericsson has made more progress, with the walkman line having the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands provide the same service and price range up to 4 000 kr, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (commonly 15 hours, generally up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe .
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, something is missing here  a virtual operator that forces traditional operators to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
The fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe has been mentioned many times on Mobil.cz.
Finally, this was confirmed by the Czech Republic, which noted that the price of SMS is higher for us than for the rest of the Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of regularizing roaming charges may lead to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
It may sound absurd, but we also have three mobile networks and coverage that is highly above 100%.
The mobile telephony operators, on the other hand, like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ) head Pavel Dvořák has also often stressed this point, saying in the past that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network no longer has many possibilities (otherwise it might be difficult to find other frequencies).
But there's another possibility - the virtual operator.
The very entry of virtual operators into the market has led to a significant price decrease, which should have been the reaction of traditional operators.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices were heard in Britain as we do.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for such workers and that they can be truly successful.
We must not go too far in the end for examples.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the mobile operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator has managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic is owned by U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can focus on a much more concrete task force.
In order to be able to function effectively, it needs far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not involve relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world, virtual operators usually come in at low cost, offering low-cost calls and SMS, which is often in line with the more restrictive service offerings.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS services that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, even betting on a not-so-distant group of money can be a pretty good move.
This operator is pointing, so to speak, specifically at men.
"Real men choose Mobilking operators they like and can trust", says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can also affirm a concept similar to that in Poland.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators rely.
Moreover, from a service point of view it is relatively saturated.'
In the Czech Republic, no possibility, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there ever is an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"There is talk of expanding this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations have little to look forward to.
Mobilking will be switched on in other countries in our area", Jana Studničková, press spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, told Mobile.cz in a telephone conversation.
He thus confirmed indirectly that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very favourable to this view.
Rather, they try to do everything they can to prevent any potential competitors from being created.
For some time now, it has been keen to launch a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group, which would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a strong interest in offering our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner you do, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them", says group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information suggests that we may have the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, an impenetrable wall of silence stands around his creation.
'At the moment we do not believe that there is room for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no one with a complex and serious project has come to us", Vlastimil Sršeň of Telefónica O2's press section told Mobil.cz in his statement.
The specificity of the Czech market is also the subject of other operators.
T-Mobil press spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with O2 statement: "So far we have not seen any business project that is vital and beneficial to both of us, on which to build on".
He adds: "There will hardly be a virtual operator on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
We should have had a concrete agreement at this stage before the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon.'
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting its 3G licence requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the customer's point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common high-speed mobile internet network.'
Competent authorities - with the accompanying operators
The attitude of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to lower profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The troubles surrounding the creation of the U:fon show that when operators are interested in something they can row from the same side.
Perhaps the pressure was on ČTÚ at the time of the creation of U:fon towards T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from ČTÚ's webpages.
But now U:fon is just an argument for not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová observed: 'The competitive environment in the mobile market has been only recently strengthened, especially with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
As regards the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on him and above all on his services.'
The attitude of mobile operators is, however, surprisingly uninteresting in the Czech regulatory authorities.
It is not only the attitude of the CTU that unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - it has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
The Commission has also proposed a new proposal for a directive on the protection of workers' rights.
This, however, took its typical position in the face of the whole problem.
'The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the necessary infrastructure lease agreement between the mobile operator and the virtual operator has been concluded.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the potential buyers' offer has probably not been attractive enough for traditional operators", said Kristián Chalupa, from the ÚOHS External Relations Section, in response to our question.
This statement by the operators' representatives may not come as a surprise.
But the office, which must defend the interests of consumers and ensure that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, is more than a delicate matter.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the overseas countries where virtual operators commonly operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services".
But of course pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and price reductions are not in the interests of the OHIM.
What is truly shocking about the whole situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three actors resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is a matter of opinion.
The same price for petrol for all petrol stations is certainly the result of coincidence and competition.
'The Section has found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No trader has a dominant position and therefore has no correspondingly greater responsibility for its market behaviour.
The telecommunications regulator may also lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile network market for virtual operators,' Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of dominant position in the market is one of the many controversial points .
There is of course the relevant market analysis carried out by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are the only market in terms of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different approach - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has - logically - the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion, it has to be dominant.
But even if we do not admit this argument, it should be a little alarming for the UOHS that three mobile operators are doing so strangely similarly.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all operators.
The Commission has already taken the necessary steps to ensure that the Commission is able to take the necessary measures to ensure that the Commission is able to take the necessary measures to ensure that the Commission is able to take the necessary measures.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not promoted until the recent Telecommunications Act was updated, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve.
This is something that the representatives of the UOHS must know better than they do, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
You can do it when no one's looking
We are not aware of the functioning of these pseudo-virtual operators, some of which are even present in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only pre-established persons.
The magic is that the company is a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer, he then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
'If the cases you are talking about, which we will be interested in, arise, it could be a breach of contractual conditions and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with that company,' Martina Kemrová replied to the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, thousands of customers can be involved.
No operator is defending himself against such an attitude at the same time.
The fact that these companies are not indifferent to their business is that they make a profit and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not harmed in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, and therefore cannot have it in full as regular customers of mobile operators.
But that's exactly what should be a little strange to the CTU.
In addition, another question arises for the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to this attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It must be added that the OHIM has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not, it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and whose business conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has been stated several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant decrease in prices for services.
At the same time, in almost all countries where operators were born, traditional operators were trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were pretty much identical - too small a market, too saturated a limit, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in developed countries, regulators have intervened in these very cases, not to defend mobile operators but their customers.
Both with formal measures and with informal pressure, then came the creation of the first virtual operator and others came to him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves off each other like a hot potato.
We cannot, in our experience, get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity in these cases makes them more than comfortable.
But we're not throwing the sponge.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator will appear to us very soon, the Czech mobile market will start again.
If one of the operators had agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it is unlikely that ÚOHS would remain impassible to the rejection (discrimination) of the other operators concerned.
And we may stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
