The Prague MHD will accompany you for the first time with an electronic card
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be written in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will board the metro, tram and buses with an electronic card in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
Right now , about 100,000 people who have their own Opencard can get it .
Passengers can purchase the 30-day and 90-day annual card (starting on 1 January 2009) and at the same time charge their card at the Infopoints and the Transport Company offices and at the Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
The vouchers can be purchased online from yesterday on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
More than 400 customers benefited from the service before noon.
Those who will start using the Internet service can completely forget the railway stations where they used to line up for paper tickets.
The cutting is purchased online and recharged on the Opencard at one of the 12 branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places passengers have a trained staff gateway that will help them make their online purchases and will also record their credit card", said Martin Opatrný, project spokesman.
In addition to the library, it will be possible to upload the electronic vouchers to the Opencard ATMs and self-service machines that are installed at the subway entrances.
What are these ATMs like?
They are red, resemble ticket wipers and passengers have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stops.
"There are now five in the whole city but by the end of the year there should be eighty", Opatrný concluded.
The cutting will be controlled by the driver instead of the ATM.
The ATM service that will be running from tomorrow is very simple.
Just insert the Opencard card and after you pay the cutting, it will load on top.
Electronic cards are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, on the urban train and bus lines from 300 to 499, which the inhabitants of the municipalities of central Bohemia take to reach the capital.
"In the train systems added to Prague integrated transport there are card reader controllers which check the timing and zonal validity", explained the method of checking tickets Filip by the organisation Ropid, which sets the timetables for public transport in Prague.
The buses have card readers integrated into the driver's case.
During the climb, it is therefore necessary not only to show the magnetic card to the driver, but also to support the Opencard at the specified point next to the box.
So the driver checks the validity of the loaded logs.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the charged cards, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this kind of information", Drápal added.
Passengers who take city buses and do not remember, when the card expires, can go back to the self-service ATMs, where they load the cards onto paper.
Here you will see the validity information of your documents on the screen of the device.
The Sudeten Germans wanted a referendum from the US
The Sudeten Germans in 1945 asked to include Šumava in the United States.
This is shown in the letter deposited in the South Bohemian Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live under the patronage of the United States.
With this desire, some Sudeten German groups reportedly turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This is primarily the result of the letter kept in a private archive and now deposited in the South Bohemian Science Library.
The Germans of Český Krumlov ask the US President in their letter not to allow the return of the "Sumava district" occupied by Hitler under the Munich Agreement to Czechoslovakia.
"We understand the situation and want to be sure of the promises that American units will come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", the letter, signed with the words "People who care about the fate of Šumava with all their heart", reads.
Since, they say, the annexation of Czechoslovakia  knowing the Czech national character - gives Sudeten Germans hope only in brutality, disregard, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to assume the protectorate over Šumava now and forever.
"We cannot believe that without respect for the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you would recognize this territory as a state alien to us, which oppresses and eradicates ethnic minorities and has contributed in no way, in no way, to the victory of the Allies", it says in the letter.
