In a city apart, pride and trials of a black life
Hidden in the theme park stretching out over the Orlando suburbs, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the gigantic, quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come to life.
Eatonville, the first all-black incorporated town in the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools, and no prison".
It's a place of pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect for Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city you described -- and that makes tourists stop by including it in the Florida tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers' Project -- remains a place in its own right.
It's as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with white men, who "knowing so little about us, don't know what they're missing".
Even now, in a year where a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, was invited to give an opening speech on race, many here remain suspicious of the outsider's gaze.
"We are very careful about how our story is told", said 59-year-old Hortense Jones, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It must be right".
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It's both a historic pattern of black power grab and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example of the oak shadow of the rural culture of the black people of the South - sometimes despised, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really started with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books, such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through the often-forgotten center of Florida into a scene of black history and human drama.
Low as a crutch in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clarke, and then deviated to more private areas.
"Out of the street on the left", he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white finishes, with its well-kept gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could only read and write".
She also mentioned the widow's new husband Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and whatever fits the passing rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly, this wasn't Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
"Zora was telling it like it was", said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls who Hurston immortalized quoting men singing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it".
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who often returned from his family's move to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, remembers that when Hurston was driving into the city, he would usually arrive without warning in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts of decent clothing.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin says, while others were submissive.
"People were always very happy to see Zora", said Mr. Franklin.
But, she added, rolling over in her chair in the backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a plaque-less grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no big memorial ceremonies, and no big conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A change occurred in the 1980's.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-lane road.
Orlando's expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the city's western boundary.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had ended the idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community's doorstep.
"During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and stuff at people sitting on one side", says Mr. Franklin.
"In fact, we had a girl who was killed by that once.
They threw a cucumber out of a car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston petitioned the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school board "an insult rather than an honor for my race".
Residents now say that the desegregation of schools, despite some positive aspects, is diluting Eatonville's cohesion and jeopardizing the confidence of its youth.
"Black kids were used to being hugged - I remember this - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening", said N. Y. Nathiri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher... - I mean, there's a cultural divide there", said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped and made room for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - a black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudice, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines like, "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I really don't understand".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway hit bookshelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project came as his most famous daughter had reworked the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a lifeguard.
The community began planning a festival in 1988 dedicated to Hurston to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans attended the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the memorial.
Many years later, the state withdrew from its road project.
"The five lanes of the revived highway, brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city", Ms. Nathiri said.
Mrs. Boyd put it simply: "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory over the highway project helped change the city's image of itself.
Those from out of town like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, started appearing in large numbers, and residents started reevaluating the past.
Eatonville was added to the public register in 1998.
A new one-story bookstore (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a re-floored and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly in Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a secondary road in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1800s.
(He's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to look for Eatonville's history, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A prior request for permission is required for most interviews, and some things -- like murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, showing black men in the fields -- are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a fat, bright red teacher, still fears that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet as the Hurston Festival expanded, a high level of civic pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, troubled and everything, no better, no worse and proud, creative, hardworking, dumb and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It's a sincere civic affection what can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the Police Department, who said he might need help.
And even younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned how to describe Eatonville properly.
"Many people, if they've just come in here, will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said after the Mass on a recent Sunday.
"But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it's a really nice city".
