Recurring drunk drivers will have to install an alcohol lock.
The Ministry of the Interior requires drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol use to install in their car the system that prevents driving while intoxicated or if they are not breathing in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Prosecutor General, according to which it will be a pilot project of one year.
The purpose of this project is to reintegrate the driver, since he will have to attend a road rehabilitation course.
In addition to the Attorney General for Road Safety, the Directorate-General for Traffic (DGT) and the Foundation for Automotive Safety Technology (FITSA) will also participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers who report drunk driving more than once return to driving.
Alcolock would avoid this, because it is a vehicle-connected system that measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver is not breathing, or when a higher than permitted alcohol concentration is detected.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned person.
In this regard, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles fitted with such devices can reduce infringements committed during the first year of introduction by up to 65%.
And in Spain, it's estimated that it could save 115 lives a year.
The measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: to curb these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means, and, no doubt, the reform necessary for criminal procedure would require organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been experimentally introduced in some industrial and public vehicles.
The European Parliament will vote on a PSOE initiative to install this system in school buses tomorrow, as has already been done in France.
