Speaking in Your Sleep
Some children talk at night.
I'm not talking about those who wake up very anxious to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but those children who talk while they're asleep.
The first time it happens, you're scaring at most, but it doesn't really matter much.
It's a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquy.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This can occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example associated with a high fever episode) or more regularly (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes these are episodes linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night sweats (bed peeing), or sleepwalking, but this is not necessarily the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stressful situations or over-excitation.
In any case, it is still a relatively new phenomenon.
The intensity of its appearance is also extremely variable.
It may happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (hurry, scream, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be wise to observe the child and, if necessary, to consult a specialist to see if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet for the situation.
We said that this is a benign alteration and therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stressful situations).
What can be done, however, is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to over-excite the child before he goes to bed.
To promote calm games and to avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children who find it difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the baby to sleep more peacefully.
Once the sleepwalkers appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's unaware of what's going on, and you'd interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember, if you seem very anxious and the episodes are frequent, it is best to see a doctor or to see where such anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You'll get nothing, because he's asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thinking.
In addition, you can hear what he says but not see what he dreams to say, so you have to pay close attention to the interpretation of information and the conclusions it may lead to.
Never tell your child that you can ask him questions at night to learn his secrets.
Not even a joke.
Something like that causes a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing serious, it's just a few minutes long episode.
