The encounter - Blood is safe again
HEMA-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, as HEMA-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained the public's trust, seriously shaken by the blood-infected scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves run by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and public protests, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994 led by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at shedding light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent a similar disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was delaying a report, some provinces set up a committee to devise a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Québec and Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, only 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was heartbreaking.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve blood test safety and field research over the following years, we have regained public trust", she explains before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec's population now trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases of the human variant of the mad cow in Europe, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the woman who has been its president since 1998.
"And we had no idea if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
We therefore based this on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, which states that when you have doubts and you may have a serious illness, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which manifests itself with a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures are taken.
In April 1999, blood was refused to those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980.
Now, for some years now, it has been shown that this disease is undoubtedly transmitted through infected blood.
This episode thus showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle".
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NTAs) that allow the presence of the virus in the blood of donors to be directly recognized, rather than antibodies against the virus, which were the basis of the tests used up to that time.
TANs have reduced the window period, from the time the person contracted the disease to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood through our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period could be reduced to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to identify them has been greatly reduced.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS by blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood samples will have to be distributed before anyone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years for a transfusion-transmitted HIV case to be detected.
I believe that today one can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to restore health, says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the bloodstream by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant,' continues Dr Décary, before stressing that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"Needs increase as the population ages.
Since cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has implications for the number of donors, which on average only make up 3% of Quebecers eligible as donors.'
However, all healthy persons who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who offer to be donors are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the disease is prevalent, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we can maintain an inventory that can meet the needs of hospitals.
The cases of shortages are very rare.
But the members of this group of donors need to be renewed as they age and are no longer able to donate.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to withhold it and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that it is hard to find an hour to donate blood", says bereaved Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at Héma-Québec, which operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, once considered a biomedical waste, abounds with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the bank entry of our 1,000th cord blood sample and expect to take more than 1,000 each year.
They should be proposed for transplantation early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection practice as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it", as Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
