Free Speech - The Orwellian Speech of Barrick Gold
In the 17 September issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr Patrick J. Garver, Vice President and Managing Director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing Orwellian logic, the latter claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a six million defamation suit against three authors and a small, squattered publishing house with the intention of launching a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in defamation cases, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden by Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to take a stand against his own.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and publishers of the book Canada Black will have to spend a considerable sum of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with decidedly unlearned weapons, against an army of lawyers financed by the pockets of the mining company with virtually no funds.
In these unprecedented armed conflicts, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that will silence the opposition and to frighten anyone who dares to speak out again on the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public that it should have presented its own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada debates are normally held by exchange of views and not by a slam dunk.
It would have been enough for the company to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and funding independent research teams that could shed light on the matter.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to have much confidence in the public and badly rejects petitions and letters in support of the Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can call for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same audience is clearly evident?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to the well-paid lawyers and not to the whole of Canada; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even the denigrators have a say.
What Barrack Gold doesn't understand  or doesn't want to understand  is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Canada Black does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and judge, but based on civilian exchanges of opinion, and not in the perspective of what many perceive as a kind of mugging (in pursuit of the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just issued an ultimatum to the authors of Canada Black urging them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver's surreal discourse, the lawsuit brought by Barrack Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It blocks the right to quote authentic sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss uncomfortable topics for the world's richest companies, and to file multiple lawsuits, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific norms as do the authors of Black Canada.
You have a right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to handle debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is at the expense of the university world, as well as the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit abusive lawsuits.
Operation - rescue for Wall Street  Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and the top congressional leaders, representatives of the Republican and Democratic parties, yesterday finally reached an agreement on the largest savings plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan, which aims to curb the financial crisis that has been plaguing Wall Street for months, still needs to be ratified by both houses of Congress.
It provides in particular for checks on the effective implementation of the scheme by elected leaders, new mechanisms to guarantee the reimbursement of public money, new arrangements to contain the number of houses foreclosed on for failure to pay, and a right to inspect the salaries paid to the managers of the protected enterprises.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican negotiator Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress toward an effective market agreement", said Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson.
"Every decision has been made to protect the American economy and people from the current crisis on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"It's the crucial point: if we hadn't acted this way, invaluable upheavals and upheavals would have been poured into the daily lives of Americans", said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a further bankruptcy on investors.
The deadline agreed was for the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates for the US presidency, who joined the negotiations later, were rather supportive of the agreement, but did not hesitate to express their dissatisfaction with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama is credited with adding some provisions to the agreement, in particular one that will allow owners to maintain their homes and one that concerns salaries for managers of state-owned enterprises.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary", he commented on the American television screen.
Interviewed on another channel to ask if he would vote for the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I'd like to analyze the details, but I hope so".
"From what I've read, it's something we all have to digest and it'll keep us going".
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable", he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to use taxpayer money to buy back the dubious credits, risky assets and irrevocable assets of American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the bursting of a housing bubble that led first to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (mutuations), then to extend to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and resulted in liquidity freezes and the dissolution of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans in charge that aired the first draft of a deal last week.
It seems they have been out of the loop since the Democrats accepted that the "toxic" assets of some struggling companies are only protected by the government, rather than bought.
In order to meet everyone, a provision was added to the Congress that if the government were to face losses over the next five years because of this programme, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for an initial payment of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion could be added if the President deems it necessary.
The 350 billion payment should be ratified by a further vote of Congress.
In return for his help, Washington will get a stake in the protected companies that will pay dividends on profits and sell it back when the waters calm down.
The plan provides that the Federal Government will be able to delay foreclosure procedures for real estate loans and to set limits on the remuneration and start-up allowances paid to the managers of the undertakings involved.
