What was produced at the Zuschlag & Associates factories?
The hearing of the criminal case against János Zuschlag and his associates will be held shortly, on 8 October.
The politician and his associates are charged with repeated commercial fraud committed within a criminal association that caused considerable damage, and other crimes, including forgery of documents.
The Prosecutor's Office said that the money obtained from the bids was used by them for private purposes and that they often certified the activities by means of false invoices.
The state and municipal money, totalling 65 million florins, ended up in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, in some cases in the pockets of some people.
According to the method disclosed by the investigating authorities, they withdrew the money obtained from the tendering procedures on the basis of invoices for non-existent transactions and the associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were false.
For the purpose of making them, the invoice blocks were purchased at the market in Józsefváros, while the circular stamps were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on which company to issue the invoices, it was established, among other things, during the hill trip over Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter's confession he had to choose pensions and restaurants.
He asked for a bill for consumption, and the model of these was followed by the preparation of the invoices to be submitted to the tenderers, including those of the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the Municipality of Budapest.
A large part of these are the work of István Lados and András Őri who, according to our information, has written the reports necessary to obtain the financing.
One of the choices of Lados' "study trip" was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and partners in 2003, the restaurant provided meals for a group of 90 persons from Biztos Pont Egyesület.
So many people, however, according to the restaurateur, wouldn't all go into the restaurant together.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, was full of formal and substantive errors.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay overnight, however, the bill included 130 guests.
But the compilers of the fancy invoices exaggerated when they reported Pigal Kft., also a restaurant company, whose accounts - according to the information provided to the judicial authorities - did not even include documents on behalf of the companies Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the company's director, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he immediately realized that they were fake documents.
"On the stamp the name and the match of our company Iva were in the wrong place".
He added that, apart from the formal reasons, there was no mention of the fact that according to the bill, 100 people were accommodated, when they have 11 rooms in total and there are not so many beds.
By the time the bill came through, it was catering and their restaurant had been out of business for a while.
The regular invoicers did not bother to learn that the Budapest travel agency of their choice only organises travel abroad, so they foolishly indicated on the invoice that they were paying in cash for travel to Hungary, which was not in line with the company's invoice-issuing practice.
In addition, as demonstrated during the investigation, VAT was also included in the invoice, while travel to countries outside the European Union is VAT-free.
The amount of the Iva was also incorrect on the four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favour of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, as the company's services were subject to the 15% and not the 25% VAT rate indicated on the invoices, and the hotel employees only issued printed invoices, while the invoice was handwritten.
In addition, the 'issuers' have ruined other invoices, in the case of a firm they have indicated as activity carried out by road freight transport, as is known from the prosecutor's proceedings, which was not carried out by the company originally established as an investment consultancy.
Furthermore, it was found that the invoices issued in favour of Együtt in Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont, of XXI, were false because of formal defects - a case formulated in non-conform invoice, a false stamp.
The same was true of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó Sports Field, whose representatives denied having issued the invoices in question.
The counterfeiters also failed to pay attention to the fact that HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation when a group from Fiatal Városért Egyesület had lunch there in 2001 and that is why the company's liquidation curator, according to our information, denied that he had issued that invoice.
