The psychology of over-bidding: Why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers are more likely to spend more, to overvalue goods.
Neurologists and economists at New York University have uncovered the neuroeconomic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study in the journal Science, men do not want to lag behind in a bid like eBay's auction, so they are willing to pay a higher price.
Researchers have tried to trace the nervous pattern of this "game" at the nervous system level through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games, participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the main element is bidding more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex gets intensively functioning when you lose the game.
This area of the brain, along with other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-gratification" of the nervous system.
So the researchers say the price hike is explained by the intense reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, the economists in the research group conducted a financial follow-up survey.
In this investigation, three groups tendered against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the actual value of the product concerned and made its bet.
Another group, besides this, was promised another $15 prize if they won.
The third group would receive $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would lose money if they lost at the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
By testing the neurologist's hypothesis, the members of the "loss" group were willing to bet higher than the control group or "win".
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These have hitherto explained the phenomena of auctioning with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we have come to a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's School of Economics.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
Nearly half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while chronic liver disease is the leading cause of death in Hungary.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients is 100,000, of which only 7,000 are treated.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name for infectious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical of which are hepatitis and yttrium, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. infected water and food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal leaks, saliva).
For travelers, it's helpful to get vaccinated against A and B viruses, there's no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellow spots form on the skin and white of the eyes, the stool becomes clear and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancers and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason is that only one in ten people is estimated to receive drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause cirrhosis of the liver and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know they have the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, often with the first symptoms appearing after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and conduct regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
In the world today, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since a routine laboratory examination also reveals the disease, it is worthwhile to see a family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
When the disease is recognized in time, it can be cured, the virus can be eliminated from the body, thus ceasing its infectious power and preventing the formation of tumors.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by the World Association of Hepatitis.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, its causes of development and early detection.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to a recent survey, religious faith works as a sort of pain reliever that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more tolerable.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God influences the feeling of pain, reported the British Telegraph.
As part of the rather bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out on 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists as possible, while all were watching a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholic believers were able to repel much of the pain.
Through the research technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first in a series of studies involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from the University.
The test went exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharge and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the experiment subject.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's Hermeline painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would give rise to a religious status among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in that time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone was taking care of" them, and "they calmed down and were filled with peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image, they reported 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that a similar result can be achieved with any image with strong effect even for atheists, but the appropriate image must be found.
"We need to find an image that makes them feel very positive, like a mother or a father", said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright was pleased with the results.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality", Wright added.
After the excellent results, the only question remains whether the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on pain control?
Would the vision of a quality Virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the day of their tenth birthday, Google can claim to be in people's pockets as much as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, what kind of clinic they go to and what they care about.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's directors, that is not enough yet.
But as for the skeptics who compare themselves to the Orwellian nightmare, they don't really see the essence of Web 2.0.
Recently Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect as much personal data as possible from its users and this is necessary to adhere to the original goal of Google's founders which was: "let's put all the information in the world into one system!"
According to the Google CEO interviewed by the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it's still in the early stages of being able to handle all the information.
When asked what would happen in five years, Schmidt said: "I wish Google could answer questions like, 'What do I do tomorrow?' or 'What would be the right job for me?', but software doesn't know how to answer seemingly simple questions because it doesn't know enough about users.
Not all internet users are aware that when they search the internet, they are recorded exactly what words they are looking for, from which IP address they are searching and on which page they stop after searching.
The use of Personalized Search, launched two years ago, enables users to store their browsing history, to look up what they have searched and clicked on, and to generate much better results in the long run.
What if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - users worried about Google's data monopoly ask themselves.
In most cases, the counter-reactions of the internet users are caused by the fear felt for the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by guilt, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or even rebellion against power.
One fact is confirmed, however, that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but can also be provided to third parties in reasoned cases, in which case nothing protects the personal rights of internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times has been the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Google-run Orkut community page.
Internet users concerned about personal rights, on the other hand, sighed with relief in May when the firm - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even later, Google cannot be forced by any constitutional clause to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government has successfully seized nearly 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search terms obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still has failed to obtain individual user search lists and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who fear providing their personal data are spitting on Google because they believe that their privacy and privacy will be compromised by starting to use its services and are upset by the rebellion against the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users in many countries see in them the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", as opposed to their rival, Microsoft, liquidated as the conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both are fighting for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, doesn't ask its users for an identification code, doesn't ask for money for its services, the source code is kept updated and the program package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which involves one of the most frequently repeated keywords in recent years, Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal, and while the size of these changes for each individual, the essence is the same: show us ourselves.
A young average can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can link them to other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his musical tastes, can insert them into systems like FriendFeed or Blip.fm, and can also write blogs where his latest photo galleries are automatically displayed on Flickr or Picasa.
In the meantime, we read of numerous examples of how the girl, seeing the series of pictures taken in the morning by her friends, can easily tell who her treacherous boyfriend spent the night with or whether a company can fire an employee because he wrote a sincere opinion on the top of the company: one thing is for sure, the concept of privacy has now been completely reconsidered.
Those who live online live in a way that shows themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just avoid Google's monopoly can do so (starting with Scroogle using Google's search system but at the same time not leaving traces voluntarily).
There are not many people who don't deliberately sign up for community pages to be found, Google's online applications, from word processing to image management and news gathering, can be replaced with alternative versions that aren't tied to huge server parks and that don't make up our best profile yet.
The public is not even waiting in secret for the moment when Google will pull out the claws.
The company's $156 billion worth is now worth more than IBM's ($140 billion), Intel's ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola's ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising space threatens advertising agencies' revenues, and services introduced in record time cause major problems not only for Microsoft but also for many software development companies.
However, critical observers alongside all this find alarming points: the company summit, for example, completely rejected the protest of employees after doubling the line of the company's kindergarten, considered repeated dining for the daily pleasure of employees too expensive, but all this belittles the fact that in 2006 Google turned the head to the Chinese government and under their agreement the company will filter out all results that offend the good taste and interests of the Chinese regime.
An internal rule of the firm seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it is usable, but one thing is certain, that the predictable problems of the coming months and years will move the world to a point: while some believe that Google's scanning and archiving project of books and magazines will take on proportions such that the firm will soon be in front of the US Supreme Court, others are afraid of the Health system, in fact in this we can create our health profile with our reports, doctors and problems.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the famous Cory Doctorow's Scroogled story describes the future with Orwellian accents, where a man with Google data can be approached in a frightening way.
