The intelligent machine mimics the flight of the lobster
What better way to develop collision-control technologies than to imitate obstacle sensors found in nature?
Like the bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the horns gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic boost on how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biometric robot, a robotic miniature car with bee properties, with the ultimate goal of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really closely resembles our protective shield - Kazuhiro Doi, director of the PR and R&D technology sector, explained at the exhibition.
The role of the bee's vision is important, as it can see 300 degrees in any direction.
Engineers have used the idea of a telemetric laser to copy the function of the bee's vision.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two metres away within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a control to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second, the robot senses the obstacle and then, imitating the bee's movements, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels the size needed to avoid the accident.
This avoidance, unlike the current system, is carried out entirely instinctively.
"If it wasn't for this, the robot car wouldn't react quickly to avoid collisions", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steerability of the wheels.
So instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
BR23C is powered by lighter lithium-polymer batteries with a high energy density, which means that their lifetime is higher than lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh says the instantaneity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of the data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot needs to process some input in a matter of seconds and react.
You don't need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so you only use a few tens of Kb of memory.
You don't need a gigabytes or a megabyte of memory.
This is the first step towards developing a technology for immediate collision avoidance that Nissan predicts will be installed on standard vehicles within 10 years.
Further application may be achieved by integrating it with the GPS satellite navigation system, which avoids obstacles on the road leading to the destination.
