"Scientific findings - continues the EU official - present a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most is that we must raise awareness among consumers and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with new technology".
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should take a decision on the application of the directive to the Member States.
'Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with the Member States and stakeholders what measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable musical instruments and related equipment.'
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical equipment to 100 dB, but concerns are growing about the hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
These damages can be greatly reduced by reducing noise levels and exposure duration.
In its opinion, the European Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical equipment who listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the current limits on maximum permissible noise at work.
Those who listen to music in these conditions for longer periods risk permanent hearing loss after a period of five years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
