The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already been manifested a few days ago with the House vote against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were, and are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
The New York Times confirmed this yesterday by informing us that the ongoing crisis is tearing apart the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, pro-federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, conservative, hostile to those in Washington and the world of finance, strong especially in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, by the way, which has become overwhelmingly alive with the vote I mentioned at the beginning.
But this is just one example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake may be predicting or already leaving to be seen: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not only here.
In both the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to act as an accelerator of long-incubated phenomena that solidify in the new climate and finally come to light.
The first of these is the realignment, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of state sovereignty in relation to a sort of renalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions which have, yes, close links with foreign countries, but which first and foremost involve very broadly the balance sheets of individuals and families living in one country, in one State.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who are also elected officials.
I mean, the crisis seems economically global but politically it's almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be essentially out of the game or to have little to say: the clear proof is given by the European Union, which is divided as usual between different interests and different state strategies and is unable to decide on any common policy.
And so it is that from the government of each individual state everyone expects interventions, rescue and rescue plans, new rules, and above all, funding: since when you get to the bottom of it, only the states have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to get things right.
They also have the necessary means and the right to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, under certain circumstances, which no market or international organization will likely ever have in a comparable way.
This new emphasis on the national-state element is also in perfect harmony with the growing importance that recent economic developments tend to attach to a factor closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the realm of the net, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the intangible, while we were convinced that the globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future would instead have to increasingly deal with those very intangible things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look at it a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth but are still absolutely bound to a confined space, to a territory.
So whoever is in charge of it certainly has several more cards than whoever is not, who is unlucky to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second news, however, which predicts a fracture.
Whoever says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand for someone who can take matters into their own hands.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing, economically-specific leaders, turned out to be so inadequate and full of shadowy areas.
And together something even deeper and in a sense disturbing: a discredit, a lack of suffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in a growing number of Western countries.
That is, it seems to be increasingly taking place, in a wide range of people, the belief that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites that have been in power so far, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall acceptance of the term, they have made their own time and are increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, undergroundly fuels a branched but powerful movement to delegitimize the ruling classes and traditional political backgrounds, which manifests itself in the sudden electoral uprisings or the sudden upheavals of the collective mood of recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
It seems that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats, some would say, are making it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not now taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and that the economic crisis is reinvigorating, growing, potentially agitating to the brink.
In the face of all this, talking about a 'mass rebellion' on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not at all.
